AB  - Sweden, with a population of less than 1.5 million people, rose from relative obscurity to the most powerful state in northern Europe in the period 1560 to 1720. Her natural resources were efficiently exploited for export production of copper, steel and tar for which Sweden had a dominant position on the world market. This export provided the financial means for an aggressive policy and made it possible for Sweden to sustain almost uninterrupted warface for more than a century. Key factors were the very favourable spatial availability of ore, waterpower and forest but also the state plan and control of metal production based on a sustainable utilization of the forests. In the light of the historical development in Europe, Sweden's production basis and the way it was gouverned is analysed. A comparison is made with Switzerland, a nation with about the same population, but lacking exploitable resources, except people and cattle. In the next issue of this journal a system overview will be presented using energy, not money, as scale on the exchange in the mid-17th century between Sweden and the rest of Europe by the trade and by the military operations. Such a biophysical approach throws light on the role of energy and forest for wealth and power.
