AB  - Nordahl Grieg (1902-1943) is known to Norwegian schoolchildren for his poems of defiance after the German attack on Norway in April 1940. Rather less is known about his past as a communist intellectual. His biographers have discussed the theme, but they have not had access to the Russian archive sources used in this article. In 1927, Grieg was already established in Norway as a well-known author, poet, critic and playwright. He left for China in January that year to cover the Chinese civil war for Norwegian newspapers. In China he befriended the chief Comintern advisor to Guomindang, Mikhail Gruzenberg, alias Borodin, who had lived in Norway a few years earlier and obviously took a keen interest in the young Norwegian. Through Borodin, Grieg came into close contact with Madame Sun Yat-sen, who still played a central role in Guomindang politics. It seems that his stay in China had a decisive influence on him. At the very least it made him receptive to the logic of the revolutionary role of the Soviet Union in culture, economics and society. However, there are numerous doubts as to his political inclinations in the following years. While Norwegian radical at the time considered him a reactionary, the word "fascist" was even used, we know that his immediate family was of conservative stock, and that he was financially dependent on his brother, the publisher Harald Grieg of the Gyldendal publishing house. Many years later, Harald Grieg related that his brother had embarked on a revolutionary path at least by 1932. Nordahl Grieg went to the Soviet Union in February 1933 to study theatre, and did not return to Norway until December 1934. In Moscow, the Authors' Union took him under their wing and he became a close friend of the Russian author Boris Pilnyak and studied theatre under Vsevelod Meyerhold. He fell in love with a Russian woman, Vega Linde, with whom he lived for some time. After his return to his native town of Bergen, he made a reputation for himself as an outspoken defender of everything the Soviet Union stood for, from art to politics and war war in the case of Finland. His plays were inspired by revolutionary theatre, and they all were severely critical of the prevailing society in the West. His most important contribution to the cause of the Soviet Union, though, might have been the political journal Veien Frem in 1936-37. Financially, it was supported by the Comintern, and he received editorial guidance from VOKS, the Organisation of Cultural Relations with Foreign Countries under the Communist Party of the Soviet Union. The defiant and militant Stalinist woman of Kira Dimitrovna from his 1938 novel Ung Ma Verden Ennu Vaere became the symbol for Norwegian communists of the time. Seen in this perspective, Nordahl Grieg became what has been called a communist cultural worker. However, with the advent of war in 1940, his role changed, if not his attitude. For the rest of his days he came to symbolise Norwegian resistance to the German occupation of Norway. He was killed in December 1943 aboard a British bomber shot down over Berlin.
