AB  - We tested the role of matrix type as a determinant of changes in bird densities associated with patch area (patch size effect) by studying bird distribution in two different landscape contexts: forested islands in archipelagos (low quality matrix) and mature forest patches in landscape managed by forestry (high quality matrix). We predicted that patch area effects (PAE) will be stronger in patches surrounded by a low quality matrix in which movements of individuals are more restricted and alternative resources not available. We assessed the role of species sensitivity to human induced landscape change (estimated from species population trends in long term monitoring data) as a predictor of patch size effect in forest. birds in different landscape scenarios. Overall patch area effects were significantly higher than 0 in real islands but not in patches surrounded by a higher quality matrix. Species more sensitive to large-scale landscape change showed strong patch size effects on islands but not in fragments. Our results suggest that forest fragments do not function as real islands mainly because of the compensatory effects of the surrounding matrix. However, the significant association between large-scale population trends and species responses at a local level in patches surrounded by a low quality matrix suggests that strong changes in landscape matrix quality might be behind recent population decreases of some boreal forest birds.
