AB  - Technological revolution, change of techno-economic paradigms, globalization transformed the world economy's structure and reorganized people's lives. During many years of discussion about how to deal with the huge architectural, ecological and social-cultural heritage of the Industrial age they have concluded that unconcerned destruction of former enterprises would lead to the loss of the entire historical layer. A way out has been found in re-use of buildings, museumification of the selected mining industrial territories, underground space, using them for recreation.
   The society's interest in such examples of the industrial past is related to their uncommon anthropogenic landscape, cultural value and educative resource.
   Despite many examples of re-use of mining-industrial heritage immovable items, consistent theoretical approaches to the estimation of cultural value and economic capacity of such objects have not been developed by now. Consequently, they try to convert every plant that ceased its industrial activity into a monument thus multiplying their total quantity and devaluing the very concept of "heritage". The authors of the article generalize practical experience on studying historical-geological resources in Russia and Finland, suggest general methodical basis for the prospective assessment of these objects' commercialization to be developed. An integrated cross-disciplinary character of works on introducing the sites of mining-industrial heritage into tourist turnover and the need in scientific support of works should be noted.
   Science opinion is to be made for every object of mining-industrial heritage that is potentially considered as a tourist site. The analysis includes assessment of its unique character, visual performances, degree of it preservation (what to show) and information richness (what to tell), convenience of geographic location, ecological performance and safety requirements. Based on the analysis volume of investments in the object to create baseline conditions for safe and comfortable recreation is derived.
   Mining-industrial heritage objects are demanded economic resources and can be seen as a prospective source of economic growth for local societies. Comprehensive scientific study of such potential sites of tourist interest is the most important component for preparing them to be introduced into tourist turnover.
