AB  - The aim of sustainable development of natural resources is to secure national prosperity in all its different forms without reducing the benefits derived from the environment.  Finland has adopted this long-term approach to the exploitation of forest resources since the 1920s.  Forestry has centuries of tradition in using different sustainability concepts as the basis for forestry policy, explains Professor Matti Palo in the article on pages 21-25.
   The idea of sustainable forestry can be interpreted in different ways.  At a superficial level, forestry is sustainable when there is no decline in the area of land devoted to growing forest.  It can also be taken to mean no decline in the volume of wood felled, the growing stock of trees, income from forestry or in the properties of forest ecosystems.
   In terms of forest growth and age-class distribution, the scope for felling in Finland's forests is growing at an almost unbelievably fast rate.  Even if forest damage due to air pollution, etc.  were to increase, the supply of wood needed to meet the forest industry investments of the 1990s looks secure.
