AB  - Samples of 1) suspended load and 2) overbank sediment were collected from three Norwegian rivers. Suspended sediment transport was calculated on the basis of 1-4 samples a day in the frost free periods of 1987-1993, while chemical composition of suspended sediment was determined on samples collected once a week. Samples of vertical sections of overbank sediment were collected once. The samples were analyzed for the acid soluble fraction of 29 elements of which 6 are treated here. The short-term variations of particulate element transport rates seem to be more dependent on sediment transport rates than on element concentration. Short-term variations of the chemical composition of suspended sediment were caused by variations in the chemical composition of the sediment sources, or by secondary effects such as variations in grain size. Based on sedimentological observations and radiogenic dating of the overbank sediment, it is suggested that major floods are key factors controlling long-term availability of sediment in Norwegian rivers. In the watershed of the Knabana-Kvina river, mining activities have increased sediment transport rates and caused up to 40 times increase of Mo-concentrations in overbank sediment. The chemical composition of the suspended load is still influenced by the mine waste 20 years after the mine has been closed.
