AB  - An underground car park for 537 cars was constructed 1995-1997 in a new suburb built in the district of Herttoniemi, in eastern Helsinki, Finland. The car park was designed and equipped for use as a civil defence shelter for 9000 persons to serve the population of the area in time of need. The building of an underground car park in rock allowed more efficient land use and avoided fragmentation of housing developments typified by surface car parks. An underground solution at the same time produced rock rubble needed for other development areas acid helped reduce the total investment cost. The car park comprises six single story parking halls, five pedestrian entrances and a single vehicle ramp linking to the local road network. The total excavated volume is 77,489 m(3) and the total floor area is 17,706 m(2). Construction was completed in 24 months, as a result of the use of modem construction methods. A thorough ground investigation programme, careful consideration of 'buildability' and detailed rock mechanics calculations meant that work on site proceeded without any unexpected problems.
